Dialogue: 0,0:01:44.02,0:01:48.94,Sign,,0,0,150,,{\blur1\b1\bord0\shad0\fade(400,400)\fs30\c&HEADBD2&}Episode 4\N\N\N\N\N\N{\fs60}First Explorations
Dialogue: 0,0:01:59.43,0:02:04.06,Default,,0,0,0,,This is our third morning \Nafter the arrival to South Australia. {Our third morning, after the arrival to South Australia, had come.}
Dialogue: 0,0:02:24.44,0:02:26.37,Default,,0,0,0,,Good morning, Mr. Poppel.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:26.37,0:02:30.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Morning, Mr. Parker. \NHow is your tent doing?
Dialogue: 0,0:02:30.00,0:02:33.34,Default,,0,0,0,,Thank you, it has never been better. \NI am no longer anxious.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:33.34,0:02:34.75,Default,,0,0,0,,Let's see.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:34.75,0:02:37.26,Default,,0,0,0,,Last night I slept in it like a log.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:38.17,0:02:40.04,Default,,0,0,0,,It will stand even if a storm comes.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:40.68,0:02:43.01,Default,,0,0,0,,Going to the city of Adelaide, are you?
Dialogue: 0,0:02:43.01,0:02:46.56,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes. If we don't hurry, \Nwe may not find{be left without} a site to assemble our house.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:46.56,0:02:48.43,Default,,0,0,0,,I'm sure you'll find a fine site.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:48.43,0:02:51.48,Default,,0,0,0,,Thank you. Still...
Dialogue: 0,0:02:51.86,0:02:52.28,Default,,0,0,0,,What?
Dialogue: 0,0:02:52.73,0:02:54.24,Default,,0,0,0,,No, nothing at all.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:54.24,0:02:58.80,Default,,0,0,0,,Since we left England, we've been through \Na whole bunch of unforeseeable hardships.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:58.80,0:03:02.80,Default,,0,0,0,,- Even now, it's not yet time to be fussy{picky}. \N- That's right! We should all do our best.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:02.80,0:03:05.62,Default,,0,0,0,,Well then. \NCome, Ben.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:05.62,0:03:06.49,Default,,0,0,0,,Okay.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:08.75,0:03:11.78,Default,,0,0,0,,Don't get lost on your way to Adelaide.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:12.19,0:03:13.21,Default,,0,0,0,,Thank you!
Dialogue: 0,0:03:26.10,0:03:30.84,Default,,0,0,0,,Lucy-May! Quit playing lest we will never get it done! {so we could get it done quick!}
Dialogue: 0,0:03:35.27,0:03:38.19,Default,,0,0,0,,I wonder if dad's party \Nhas already made it to Adelaide.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:38.19,0:03:42.68,Default,,0,0,0,,You are a dum-dum. To get to Adelaide, \Nyou have to cross over ten kilometers of forest.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:42.68,0:03:44.24,Default,,0,0,0,,There's no way they arrived.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:44.24,0:03:45.98,Default,,0,0,0,,How long is ten kilometers?
Dialogue: 0,0:03:46.70,0:03:50.71,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, it's like going from our home in England \Nto the city of Burton.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:52.48,0:03:54.94,Default,,0,0,0,,Then it's not really that far.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:56.11,0:04:01.47,Default,,0,0,0,,But they have not paved a proper road yet. \NFolks get lost in those woods every now and then.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:01.47,0:04:04.59,Default,,0,0,0,,Our dad would never get lost in the woods!
Dialogue: 0,0:04:04.59,0:04:05.25,Default,,0,0,0,,Maybe so.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:05.25,0:04:06.12,Default,,0,0,0,,{\i1}Exactly{\i0} so!
Dialogue: 0,0:04:11.75,0:04:14.98,Default,,0,0,0,,I expected this road to be rather more sophisticated.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:14.98,0:04:20.82,Default,,0,0,0,,There is, by far, not much of a choice. This is the only road \Nlinking the seashore to the city of Adelaide.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:21.49,0:04:22.53,Default,,0,0,0,,Hey, dad.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:23.04,0:04:26.41,Default,,0,0,0,,Why did they found the city of Adelaide \Nnot next to the sea?
Dialogue: 0,0:04:26.41,0:04:29.60,Default,,0,0,0,,I thought adjoining a city to the harbor \Nis a common practice.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:30.65,0:04:33.52,Default,,0,0,0,,That is so. \NEven I don't know all the details.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:33.52,0:04:39.17,Default,,0,0,0,,Whether or not the city should be founded \Naway from shore is always a subject for hot debates.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:39.17,0:04:45.99,Default,,0,0,0,,It seems utterly inconvenient for carrying miscellaneous \Ngoods off and on the ship when a city is away from harbor.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:45.99,0:04:50.18,Default,,0,0,0,,The local surveyor-general Light \Nseems to be very assertive.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:50.78,0:04:56.70,Default,,0,0,0,,Following the general's lead, the city was founded inland, \Nabout ten kilometers from the sea.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:56.70,0:04:57.98,Default,,0,0,0,,General Light?
Dialogue: 0,0:04:58.69,0:05:03.03,Default,,0,0,0,,The general is striving to build Adelaide \Ninto a perfect model colony{Lit: perfect city}.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:03.03,0:05:06.99,Default,,0,0,0,,It seems the city is being built \Nin strict compliance with the city plan.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:08.66,0:05:11.48,Default,,0,0,0,,I wonder how will the city of Adelaide fare. {Lit: I wonder what kind of city will Adelaide become.}{I don't see a way to make this sound amuzing so as to make Poppel-san laugh in the next scene}
Dialogue: 0,0:05:13.33,0:05:17.13,Default,,0,0,0,,Ben, don't set high expectations. \NThey are merely starting to build it.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:17.13,0:05:20.52,Default,,0,0,0,,It's just some isolated houses{scattered} \Namong forests and fields for now.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:20.52,0:05:22.51,Default,,0,0,0,,Not many people live in it, right?
Dialogue: 0,0:05:22.51,0:05:25.13,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes. There are mere 300 residents.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:26.76,0:05:31.12,Default,,0,0,0,,However, the immigrants will keep flocking in our steps \Nat an ever-increasing rate.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:31.12,0:05:35.71,Default,,0,0,0,,In a blink of an eye, 300 turn 600. \N600 turn 1200.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:35.71,0:05:37.10,Default,,0,0,0,,1200 turn...
Dialogue: 0,0:05:37.81,0:05:39.13,Default,,0,0,0,,2400 men.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:39.13,0:05:42.42,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes, yes. It will be growing steadily from now on.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:45.90,0:05:49.38,Default,,0,0,0,,Sis, it seems we won't have to fetch any more water.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:49.38,0:05:50.03,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:50.03,0:05:51.70,Default,,0,0,0,,We are excused to go play, then?
Dialogue: 0,0:05:51.70,0:05:53.20,Default,,0,0,0,,Ask mom first.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:53.20,0:05:54.93,Default,,0,0,0,,Where did mom go?
Dialogue: 0,0:05:54.93,0:05:58.25,Default,,0,0,0,,To Ms. Jamling's{Might as well be Jamring. Both are a long shot and hardly listed in any name directories} place. \NShe was invited for tea.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:59.67,0:06:03.98,Default,,0,0,0,,Even while living in tents like this, \Nthey are still in the mood for tea parties?
Dialogue: 0,0:06:20.94,0:06:21.86,Default,,0,0,0,,With sugar?
Dialogue: 0,0:06:21.86,0:06:23.23,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes, one spoon.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:44.27,0:06:45.73,Default,,0,0,0,,Delightful.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:46.41,0:06:50.12,Default,,0,0,0,,I think you will appreciate this black tea \Nwhen you better taste it.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:51.05,0:06:52.55,Default,,0,0,0,,How about another cup?
Dialogue: 0,0:06:52.55,0:06:55.08,Default,,0,0,0,,Thank you. If only a half then.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:55.58,0:07:00.29,Default,,0,0,0,,You don't have to restrain yourself. \NSee? I have a whole tin can full of it. {Can I call a rectangular container 'can'?🤔}
Dialogue: 0,0:07:02.95,0:07:05.86,Default,,0,0,0,,- Mom!\N- Mom!
Dialogue: 0,0:07:06.68,0:07:09.78,Default,,0,0,0,,Sis said we won't have to go fetch any more water! {Lit: We have fetched enough water so that no one would have to go for additional water. Sis said so.}
Dialogue: 0,0:07:09.78,0:07:11.01,Default,,0,0,0,,Can we go play now?
Dialogue: 0,0:07:11.01,0:07:12.66,Default,,0,0,0,,What is it with you two?
Dialogue: 0,0:07:13.06,0:07:15.55,Default,,0,0,0,,You didn't even greet Mrs. Jamling properly!
Dialogue: 0,0:07:15.55,0:07:17.45,Default,,0,0,0,,- Good morning! \N- Good morning!
Dialogue: 0,0:07:18.20,0:07:22.02,Default,,0,0,0,,Good morning. Billy should be somewhere around. \NWant to play together?
Dialogue: 0,0:07:22.02,0:07:24.69,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes! \NCan we, mom?
Dialogue: 0,0:07:24.69,0:07:29.52,Default,,0,0,0,,Let's see. Ever since we disembarked here, \Nthe two of you did me a great deal of help...
Dialogue: 0,0:07:31.93,0:07:35.23,Default,,0,0,0,,Fine then. \NLet's say you have a vacation today.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:36.97,0:07:39.48,Default,,0,0,0,,Then, I will be playing together with Billy!
Dialogue: 0,0:07:39.48,0:07:41.09,Default,,0,0,0,,Wait for me, sis!
Dialogue: 0,0:07:41.09,0:07:43.40,Default,,0,0,0,,Can't you play alone every once in a while?
Dialogue: 0,0:07:43.40,0:07:44.61,Default,,0,0,0,,I cannot!
Dialogue: 0,0:07:45.36,0:07:48.67,Default,,0,0,0,,Your family is moving to Adelaide soon, is it not?
Dialogue: 0,0:07:48.67,0:07:53.76,Default,,0,0,0,,It seems like the most probable course. {I wonder if nothing else prevents it.}\NI'm sure my husband will find a good plot there.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:53.76,0:07:57.79,Default,,0,0,0,,My spouse had left for Adelaide yesterday \Nand has not returned yet.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:57.79,0:08:01.03,Default,,0,0,0,,My, you mean he didn't even spend the night at home?
Dialogue: 0,0:08:01.03,0:08:04.43,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes, although he said \Nhe would be back by yesterday.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:04.43,0:08:07.40,Default,,0,0,0,,It sure takes him longer than expected.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:07.40,0:08:08.59,Default,,0,0,0,,It sure does.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:08.59,0:08:12.89,Default,,0,0,0,,If you enter the woods after dark, \Nreturning home might get tricky.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:12.89,0:08:14.74,Default,,0,0,0,,I thought so as well...
Dialogue: 0,0:08:14.74,0:08:17.24,Default,,0,0,0,,That's right! \NThere's nothing to worry about.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:19.81,0:08:22.29,Default,,0,0,0,,How about another cup?
Dialogue: 0,0:08:37.02,0:08:39.87,Default,,0,0,0,,Dad, I wonder if we are already halfway there.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:41.20,0:08:42.76,Default,,0,0,0,,Why? Tired of walking?
Dialogue: 0,0:08:42.76,0:08:43.37,Default,,0,0,0,,Just a bit.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:43.37,0:08:44.42,Default,,0,0,0,,We can rest a little.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:44.42,0:08:47.00,Default,,0,0,0,,It's alright. \NLet's get out of the woods sooner.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:47.82,0:08:50.78,Default,,0,0,0,,This is probably the right way... I believe.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:51.78,0:08:53.70,Default,,0,0,0,,Dad, what did you just say?
Dialogue: 0,0:08:53.70,0:08:57.12,Default,,0,0,0,,I'm saying that we did not take the wrong road.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:57.12,0:08:59.03,Default,,0,0,0,,Are you sure it's all alright?
Dialogue: 0,0:08:59.03,0:09:02.81,Default,,0,0,0,,Probably, yes. \NBut mind you, I'm going through here for the first time.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:04.06,0:09:06.69,Default,,0,0,0,,Which reminds me, \Nwe have not met anyone in a while.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:09.23,0:09:11.20,Default,,0,0,0,,Let's take a little rest after all.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:19.89,0:09:21.45,Default,,0,0,0,,Are you thirsty?
Dialogue: 0,0:09:28.33,0:09:29.32,Default,,0,0,0,,What's wrong?
Dialogue: 0,0:09:29.32,0:09:31.94,Default,,0,0,0,,It's like I've heard a human voice now.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:31.94,0:09:33.42,Default,,0,0,0,,Human voice?
Dialogue: 0,0:09:33.80,0:09:36.38,Default,,0,0,0,,I heard no such thing recently.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:36.38,0:09:37.45,Default,,0,0,0,,Okay...
Dialogue: 0,0:09:48.49,0:09:49.69,Default,,0,0,0,,Dad!
Dialogue: 0,0:09:49.69,0:09:51.58,Default,,0,0,0,,Now I heard something too.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:51.58,0:09:52.98,Default,,0,0,0,,It sounds like a growl.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:52.98,0:09:55.32,Default,,0,0,0,,Aborigines may always be around.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:55.32,0:09:56.50,Default,,0,0,0,,Aborigines?
Dialogue: 0,0:09:56.50,0:09:59.74,Default,,0,0,0,,Evidently, the sound came from this direction.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:59.74,0:10:03.26,Default,,0,0,0,,Those woods are home to aborigines, \Nso that probably was one of them.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:06.73,0:10:07.85,Default,,0,0,0,,Dad!
Dialogue: 0,0:10:09.13,0:10:11.23,Default,,0,0,0,,Someone is definitely calling for help.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:13.74,0:10:15.57,Default,,0,0,0,,We'll go to check, right, dad?
Dialogue: 0,0:10:15.57,0:10:16.63,Default,,0,0,0,,We will.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:08.25,0:11:09.97,Default,,0,0,0,,What, just a rabbit?
Dialogue: 0,0:11:09.97,0:11:11.31,Default,,0,0,0,,Ohh, it startled me.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:13.36,0:11:14.77,Default,,0,0,0,,That voice again.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:16.71,0:11:18.09,Default,,0,0,0,,This way!
Dialogue: 0,0:11:32.02,0:11:35.42,Default,,0,0,0,,You can go play there, \Nbut promise me you will listen to Billy.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:36.25,0:11:39.59,Default,,0,0,0,,But Billy is just five months older than me!
Dialogue: 0,0:11:39.59,0:11:44.47,Default,,0,0,0,,At this age, even five months make the difference. {Even five monts older is still older.}\NEither way, don't stray too far away, will you?
Dialogue: 0,0:11:44.47,0:11:47.12,Default,,0,0,0,,And don't forget to look after Lucy-May, okay?
Dialogue: 0,0:11:47.12,0:11:50.69,Default,,0,0,0,,I cannot take responsibility for that as well, mom!
Dialogue: 0,0:11:50.69,0:11:54.79,Default,,0,0,0,,How come? Why are you saying \Nyou cannot look after your little sister?
Dialogue: 0,0:11:54.79,0:11:57.04,Default,,0,0,0,,This child is not like other kids!
Dialogue: 0,0:11:57.04,0:12:01.91,Default,,0,0,0,,Once she lays an eye on a peculiar animal, \Nnothing has any sway over her daze.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:01.91,0:12:04.52,Default,,0,0,0,,When we're in a hurry, this is especially unbearable.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:05.05,0:12:07.56,Default,,0,0,0,,Today you are heading to the beach, right?
Dialogue: 0,0:12:07.56,0:12:11.10,Default,,0,0,0,,Should she see a peculiar creature there, \Nshe can watch all she wants.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:11.10,0:12:14.50,Default,,0,0,0,,If she sees a cute one, that's perfectly tolerable.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:14.50,0:12:21.26,Default,,0,0,0,,But instead, be it a centipede, a lizard, or a caterpillar{maybe 'hornworm' has a more repulsive connotation?}, \NLucy-May gets dazed by their peculiarity regardless!
Dialogue: 0,0:12:21.26,0:12:25.76,Default,,0,0,0,,Even by caterpillars? \NLucy-May, be so kind to only adore cute things.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:25.76,0:12:28.13,Default,,0,0,0,,But caterpillars {\i1}are{\i0} cute!
Dialogue: 0,0:12:28.13,0:12:29.60,Default,,0,0,0,,There, see?
Dialogue: 0,0:12:31.68,0:12:33.69,Default,,0,0,0,,You feel inclined to take this along? {Lit: You feel like bringing it?}
Dialogue: 0,0:12:34.15,0:12:36.77,Default,,0,0,0,,Mosh would also be happy to play on the beach! {I want to let Mosh play on the beach.}
Dialogue: 0,0:12:36.77,0:12:38.19,Default,,0,0,0,,He'd be slowing us down.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:38.19,0:12:41.03,Default,,0,0,0,,It's fine because I will be carrying him!
Dialogue: 0,0:12:41.61,0:12:43.05,Default,,0,0,0,,Billy turned up!
Dialogue: 0,0:12:45.51,0:12:47.10,Default,,0,0,0,,Sorry I kept you waiting!
Dialogue: 0,0:12:47.10,0:12:49.26,Default,,0,0,0,,I entrust them to your care then.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:49.26,0:12:50.08,Default,,0,0,0,,Sure!
Dialogue: 0,0:12:50.08,0:12:51.86,Default,,0,0,0,,Then, we'll be on our way, mom.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:52.16,0:12:54.33,Default,,0,0,0,,- On our way!\N- On our way!
Dialogue: 0,0:12:55.77,0:12:56.86,Default,,0,0,0,,Billy!
Dialogue: 0,0:12:58.27,0:13:02.28,Default,,0,0,0,,What about your father? \NHas he not returned from Adelaide yet?
Dialogue: 0,0:13:02.28,0:13:04.51,Default,,0,0,0,,No. Not yet returned.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:08.35,0:13:09.83,Default,,0,0,0,,Take care!
Dialogue: 0,0:13:09.83,0:13:11.27,Default,,0,0,0,,{\i1}Okay!{\i0}
Dialogue: 0,0:13:18.73,0:13:21.89,Default,,0,0,0,,Help me! Is there someone?
Dialogue: 0,0:13:30.87,0:13:32.29,Default,,0,0,0,,Mr. Jamling!
Dialogue: 0,0:13:42.45,0:13:45.69,Default,,0,0,0,,I wonder just at what point could I stray off that road.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:45.69,0:13:47.97,Default,,0,0,0,,No wonder, considering it was pitch black. {It's only natural to get lost when it's pitch black.}
Dialogue: 0,0:13:47.97,0:13:49.95,Default,,0,0,0,,Should have stayed overnight in Adelaide.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:49.95,0:13:53.95,Default,,0,0,0,,My household{/ relatives} probably went crazy worried\Nwhen I didn't make it home last night.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:56.34,0:13:58.12,Default,,0,0,0,,I'm immeasurably sorry, Mr. Poppel.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:58.12,0:14:00.54,Default,,0,0,0,,No, no. \NWe've just got back on track.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:00.54,0:14:01.36,Default,,0,0,0,,Indeed.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:01.83,0:14:03.61,Default,,0,0,0,,Put me down somewhere around here.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:03.61,0:14:05.15,Default,,0,0,0,,Get ready then.{Putting you down then.}
Dialogue: 0,0:14:11.24,0:14:13.56,Default,,0,0,0,,I sure hope you did not break your leg.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:14.21,0:14:17.14,Default,,0,0,0,,It's probably alright. \NJust a sprain, I think.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:17.14,0:14:20.74,Default,,0,0,0,,Now then, how do we get you back to your tent...
Dialogue: 0,0:14:20.74,0:14:24.46,Default,,0,0,0,,Oh, no! You were on your way to Adelaide, \Ndidn't you, Mr. Poppel?
Dialogue: 0,0:14:24.46,0:14:29.03,Default,,0,0,0,,I can't abuse your hospitality.{Please don't attach any importance to me.} Somehow, I will... \NRight! I will come crawling back home. {He uses a more artistic common idiom here, rather something like 'I will come back home, even crawling if need be.' or 'Crawling and disgraced, I'll come back home.'}
Dialogue: 0,0:14:29.03,0:14:31.66,Default,,0,0,0,,Now that I can see the road, \NI won't trouble you any more.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:34.72,0:14:40.10,Default,,0,0,0,,With that leg, there's no way you return by yourself. \NWe don't mind going to Adelaide tomorrow.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:40.10,0:14:41.11,Default,,0,0,0,,Still...
Dialogue: 0,0:14:41.11,0:14:43.54,Default,,0,0,0,,At any rate, you are too feeble for it now.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:43.54,0:14:49.20,Default,,0,0,0,,Mr. Jamling, if you cling to my shoulder, \Nyou can walk home using one leg only.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:49.20,0:14:52.51,Default,,0,0,0,,Ben, don't forget to carry along Mr. Jamling's belongings.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:52.51,0:14:53.31,Default,,0,0,0,,Okay!
Dialogue: 0,0:14:53.76,0:14:55.99,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, let's try to stand up, Mr. Jamling.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:59.75,0:15:01.94,Default,,0,0,0,,Thank you, Mr. Poppel.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:01.94,0:15:03.21,Default,,0,0,0,,Forget it.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:28.13,0:15:30.42,Default,,0,0,0,,Sand is not suited for walking at all.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:30.42,0:15:32.87,Default,,0,0,0,,It really isn't. \NMy legs already start to sore.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:32.87,0:15:34.87,Default,,0,0,0,,We did not even walk terribly far yet. {We have not even been walking that long yet.}
Dialogue: 0,0:15:34.87,0:15:38.85,Default,,0,0,0,,But at least, no other kids ever go to that place, right?
Dialogue: 0,0:15:42.56,0:15:44.08,Default,,0,0,0,,Lucy-May!
Dialogue: 0,0:15:45.15,0:15:47.69,Default,,0,0,0,,Did you forget your promise not to fall behind? {to be walking fast?}
Dialogue: 0,0:15:47.69,0:15:49.38,Default,,0,0,0,,I remember it!
Dialogue: 0,0:15:58.42,0:15:59.52,Default,,0,0,0,,What is in there?
Dialogue: 0,0:15:59.52,0:16:01.24,Default,,0,0,0,,An adorable bug{insect}!
Dialogue: 0,0:16:01.24,0:16:02.15,Default,,0,0,0,,A bug?
Dialogue: 0,0:16:04.44,0:16:05.27,Default,,0,0,0,,Look!
Dialogue: 0,0:16:07.98,0:16:10.65,Default,,0,0,0,,What a disgusting bug! \NToss it away at once!
Dialogue: 0,0:16:10.65,0:16:11.70,Default,,0,0,0,,Never!
Dialogue: 0,0:16:18.02,0:16:18.72,Default,,0,0,0,,Hey.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:19.25,0:16:23.67,Default,,0,0,0,,Now that I think of it, \Nprobably no one has ever been beyond that cape.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:23.67,0:16:25.67,Default,,0,0,0,,Right. Why won't we hurry, then.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:26.58,0:16:30.47,Default,,0,0,0,,Walking in those has become so painful. \NI should go barefoot.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:30.47,0:16:34.09,Default,,0,0,0,,Mom said we should not\Nbe walking barefoot here!
Dialogue: 0,0:16:34.09,0:16:38.75,Default,,0,0,0,,Of course she did. \NBut unless you spill it out, mom will never know. {But it's rich of you to remind me of mom's prohibitions.}
Dialogue: 0,0:16:41.18,0:16:44.56,Default,,0,0,0,,This feels so much better! \NI can walk a dozen that way! {It's perfectly fit for walking!}
Dialogue: 0,0:16:46.29,0:16:47.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Away you go!
Dialogue: 0,0:16:49.00,0:16:50.38,Default,,0,0,0,,You threw away your shoes?
Dialogue: 0,0:16:50.38,0:16:54.24,Default,,0,0,0,,Of course not. Just deposited. \NWe'll go back the same road, after all. {We'll pass through here on the way back, right?}
Dialogue: 0,0:16:54.24,0:16:56.37,Default,,0,0,0,,I still don't understand.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:56.37,0:16:59.14,Default,,0,0,0,,It's fine. Just remember{the shape of} those rocks, will you?
Dialogue: 0,0:17:00.18,0:17:01.62,Default,,0,0,0,,I'll take mine off too.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:11.84,0:17:14.01,Default,,0,0,0,,Except I'll carry them along.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:14.53,0:17:17.89,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, let's hurry to the other side of that cape!
Dialogue: 0,0:17:17.89,0:17:20.06,Default,,0,0,0,,Exploration is finally underway!
Dialogue: 0,0:17:20.41,0:17:22.63,Default,,0,0,0,,Wait for me, sis!
Dialogue: 0,0:17:40.45,0:17:45.97,Default,,0,0,0,,I really can't stress enough how sorry I am{I really did something foolhardy stupid} \Nfor compelling you to waste your whole day tending to me.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:47.29,0:17:49.59,Default,,0,0,0,,You really should stop prattling like that.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:49.59,0:17:54.15,Default,,0,0,0,,Besides, your leg is worn out too. You'd better \Nspend the rest of the way on my back. Here, get on.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:54.15,0:17:56.17,Default,,0,0,0,,Please forgive my weightiness.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:56.17,0:18:00.05,Default,,0,0,0,,We'd have a good deal of carriages passing by us in England. \NBut here, it's no one to pass by. {I hate this sentence for obvious reasons}
Dialogue: 0,0:18:00.05,0:18:01.33,Default,,0,0,0,,Oh, it reminds me!
Dialogue: 0,0:18:01.33,0:18:02.60,Default,,0,0,0,,Left something behind? {Lit: What's wrong?}
Dialogue: 0,0:18:02.60,0:18:07.65,Default,,0,0,0,,No, not about that. I believe, eventually, \Nyou are transporting all your belongings to Adelaide?
Dialogue: 0,0:18:07.65,0:18:12.07,Default,,0,0,0,,Without a doubt. I was going to Adelaide today \Nin order to hire a wagon for that.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:12.07,0:18:15.86,Default,,0,0,0,,About that — \NAdelaide is not exactly rich in wagons.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:16.49,0:18:20.66,Default,,0,0,0,,There are no wagons? \NHow am I supposed to move my luggage then?
Dialogue: 0,0:18:20.66,0:18:27.12,Default,,0,0,0,,No, I didn't say there are none. It's just that they are scarce. \NOnly a few people lived there until recently.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:27.12,0:18:30.44,Default,,0,0,0,,In absence of wagons, a cow will do. \NI don't mind an ox cart.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:30.44,0:18:32.55,Default,,0,0,0,,Ox carts are few as well.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:32.55,0:18:37.24,Default,,0,0,0,,You mean, even if I go to Adelaide to hire a cart \Nnext morning, I won't find any?
Dialogue: 0,0:18:37.24,0:18:38.68,Default,,0,0,0,,That is very likely so.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:38.68,0:18:43.92,Default,,0,0,0,,Does this mean we will have to go on \Nliving under tents in that beach camp forever?
Dialogue: 0,0:18:43.92,0:18:46.50,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, eventually, there will be some carriages.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:48.27,0:18:53.07,Default,,0,0,0,,I went through the numerous difficulties \Nof bringing a prefabricated house here from England.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:53.07,0:18:56.54,Default,,0,0,0,,But in the end, I'm unable \Nto even carry it to Adelaide from the shore.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:56.54,0:19:01.77,Default,,0,0,0,,Rome was not built in one day either. {Lit: The rates at which city is being constructed are not at all that impressive.}\NThe surveying is behind the schedule, not only in the city.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:01.77,0:19:06.31,Default,,0,0,0,,The allotment surveying is hindered as well. \NApplicants are not getting their plots.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:06.31,0:19:08.39,Default,,0,0,0,,Allotment surveying is delayed?!
Dialogue: 0,0:19:08.39,0:19:09.51,Default,,0,0,0,,That's right.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:10.07,0:19:16.28,Default,,0,0,0,,My new farm here, in South Australia... \NI came here with an idea of building an unmatched farm...
Dialogue: 0,0:19:16.28,0:19:20.41,Default,,0,0,0,,But now, seeing how I cannot even get my hands on the land,
Dialogue: 0,0:19:20.41,0:19:24.25,Default,,0,0,0,,what in the world \Ndid we come all the way to South Australia for?
Dialogue: 0,0:19:30.65,0:19:32.51,Default,,0,0,0,,What in the world for...
Dialogue: 0,0:19:35.38,0:19:36.18,Default,,0,0,0,,Dad!
Dialogue: 0,0:19:38.44,0:19:39.40,Default,,0,0,0,,Please don't.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:50.88,0:19:52.65,Default,,0,0,0,,Here! Look, here it is!
Dialogue: 0,0:19:52.65,0:19:54.45,Default,,0,0,0,,Don't be so noisy, sis!
Dialogue: 0,0:19:54.45,0:19:55.95,Default,,0,0,0,,Are you sure, Lucy-May?
Dialogue: 0,0:19:55.95,0:19:57.16,Default,,0,0,0,,I can do it!
Dialogue: 0,0:20:04.39,0:20:06.32,Default,,0,0,0,,You're just a sad sack.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:06.32,0:20:08.31,Default,,0,0,0,,This time I'll do it for sure.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:17.78,0:20:20.47,Default,,0,0,0,,Ships don't seem to ever pass through here.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:20.47,0:20:23.26,Default,,0,0,0,,We have a pretty big gulf, don't we?
Dialogue: 0,0:20:23.26,0:20:29.15,Default,,0,0,0,,We do. It was first discovered by captain Flinders. \NThey called it St Vincent Gulf.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:29.15,0:20:35.42,Default,,0,0,0,,I know that story too. Next, general Light arrived here. \NHe sailed around the bay and mapped it.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:35.69,0:20:39.55,Default,,0,0,0,,The one responsible for Adelaide planning \Nis general Light as well.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:39.55,0:20:41.40,Default,,0,0,0,,He is a great person, isn't he?
Dialogue: 0,0:20:41.40,0:20:45.99,Default,,0,0,0,,You bet! When I grow up, \NI will be going on expeditions here and there as well.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:45.99,0:20:51.52,Default,,0,0,0,,Then, it will befall on me to search for places \Ncaptain Flinders and general Light never set foot on.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:51.52,0:20:53.52,Default,,0,0,0,,I will go on expeditions too.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:53.52,0:20:55.65,Default,,0,0,0,,They'd never permit a girl to join!
Dialogue: 0,0:20:55.65,0:20:56.92,Default,,0,0,0,,I'm a resourceful one.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:58.09,0:20:59.33,Default,,0,0,0,,Forget it!
Dialogue: 0,0:20:59.33,0:21:00.64,Default,,0,0,0,,I will not do that!
Dialogue: 0,0:21:00.64,0:21:01.43,Default,,0,0,0,,Do it!
Dialogue: 0,0:21:01.43,0:21:02.07,Default,,0,0,0,,Not!
Dialogue: 0,0:21:02.07,0:21:02.67,Default,,0,0,0,,Do!
Dialogue: 0,0:21:02.67,0:21:03.15,Default,,0,0,0,,Not!
Dialogue: 0,0:21:04.16,0:21:05.72,Default,,0,0,0,,Something there!
Dialogue: 0,0:21:07.53,0:21:09.95,Default,,0,0,0,,It looked like a human. \NWhat could it be?
Dialogue: 0,0:21:09.95,0:21:13.96,Default,,0,0,0,,Don't say nonsense! \NThis place is never visited by any folks.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:13.96,0:21:17.94,Default,,0,0,0,,But I swear, I saw a head behind that cliff!
Dialogue: 0,0:21:22.43,0:21:24.74,Default,,0,0,0,,That was just a trick of your eyes.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:24.74,0:21:29.43,Default,,0,0,0,,I'm sure of having seen it! \NLook! Something is peeking over it again!
Dialogue: 0,0:21:31.12,0:21:34.12,Default,,0,0,0,,Now I have this feeling it too, \Nbut I still see naught.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:34.12,0:21:36.69,Default,,0,0,0,,Hey Billy, can you go take a quick look?
Dialogue: 0,0:21:36.69,0:21:40.79,Default,,0,0,0,,Me? But this place was never trodden by any folks!
Dialogue: 0,0:21:40.79,0:21:43.34,Default,,0,0,0,,Exactly what an adult explorer would long for!
Dialogue: 0,0:21:43.34,0:21:45.15,Default,,0,0,0,,I could go if there's two of us...
Dialogue: 0,0:21:45.15,0:21:46.80,Default,,0,0,0,,No need if we're three!
Dialogue: 0,0:22:03.97,0:22:05.88,Default,,0,0,0,,This voice is telling something.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:08.68,0:22:10.58,Default,,0,0,0,,Certainly not in English.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:22.63,0:22:24.39,Default,,0,0,0,,What it this animal called?
Dialogue: 0,0:22:24.39,0:22:27.46,Default,,0,0,0,,Must be sea lions. \NI don't think those are seals.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:27.46,0:22:28.20,Default,,0,0,0,,Sea lions?
Dialogue: 0,0:22:28.20,0:22:30.39,Default,,0,0,0,,Their mugs are kinda cute. \NYou'd never tell.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:32.39,0:22:33.19,Default,,0,0,0,,It looks at us!
Dialogue: 0,0:22:33.19,0:22:34.97,Default,,0,0,0,,They are not mordacious, right?
Dialogue: 0,0:22:34.97,0:22:39.13,Default,,0,0,0,,It's fine! If we don't act funny here, \Nnothing will happen there as well.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:39.13,0:22:40.23,Default,,0,0,0,,But aren't they scary?
Dialogue: 0,0:22:40.23,0:22:41.86,Default,,0,0,0,,There's nothing to be scared of!
Dialogue: 0,0:22:46.91,0:22:49.16,Default,,0,0,0,,I'll go take a closer look at them!
Dialogue: 0,0:22:49.55,0:22:52.66,Default,,0,0,0,,Don't! Look at those impressive teeth!
Dialogue: 0,0:22:52.66,0:22:55.62,Default,,0,0,0,,Lucy-May, looking from up here is just as good. {you really shouldn't go closer.}
Dialogue: 0,0:22:55.62,0:22:57.23,Default,,0,0,0,,I'm going there alone.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:57.23,0:22:58.80,Default,,0,0,0,,Come to your senses, don't go! {It's dangerous, you should stop!}
Dialogue: 0,0:22:58.80,0:23:00.59,Default,,0,0,0,,Just a little peek and a touch.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:00.59,0:23:01.59,Default,,0,0,0,,Don't!
Dialogue: 0,0:23:09.89,0:23:11.16,Default,,0,0,0,,Lucy-May!
Dialogue: 0,0:23:26.56,0:23:30.53,Default,,0,0,0,,We knew all too well the extents \Nof Lucy-May's love for animals.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:30.53,0:23:36.09,Default,,0,0,0,,But as she was approaching that bizarre animal \Ncalled the sea lion, we were really quaking in our barefoots. {I hence proclaim this funny (c) Perevodildo}{Feel free to fix if unappropriate}
Dialogue: 0,0:23:50.10,0:23:52.09,Default,,0,0,0,,Look out! \NLucy-May...
Dialogue: 0,0:24:03.54,0:24:11.11,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fscx95}To have the naval surgeon Dr. Dayton examine Mr. Jamling's leg, \Ndad had to row the boat out in the storming sea.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:11.11,0:24:16.16,Default,,0,0,0,,Next time in Lucy-May of the Southern Rainbow: \NSunny After the Rain.{Lit: The rain followed by good weather} Join us again!
